Collection Development with Litteratura Iuris, or, Heads Will Roll â Pic of
the Week

   August 30, 2013 by [14]Nathan Dorn

   This weekâs Pic of the Week post gives you a glimpse of, well,
   something that defies all expectationsâ¦
   [15]Litteratura Iuris

   Sifting out unwanted heads: A gruesome metaphor for collection
   development from the title page of Karl Ferdinand Hommel's Litteratura
   Iuris (second edition), 1779.

   The image above depicts an engraving of a person (arms only) shaking a
   sieve full of the dismembered heads of several species, including human
   beings, so that all of the animal heads fall out and only the human
   heads remain.Â  What could this mean?

   The engraving appears on the title page of a book entitled
   [16]Litteratura Iuris (Editio Secunda) by the German academic legal
   scholar [17]Karl Ferdinand Hommel (1722-1781).Â  Hommelâs book is a
   [18]bibliographical guide to the literature of the law.Â  In it, the
   author divides the legal literature of his day into categories and then
   presents bibliographical essays that walk the practicing lawyer through
   the maze of books and scholars for each of the various fields of law.Â
   There are essays on biblical law, on the literature of the civil law,
   on [19]canon law, on public law, on [20]customary law and others.Â
   Especially interesting are his essays on rare books, on [21]prohibited
   books and on literary fraud: plagiarism and false attributions of
   authorship.Â  The second part of the book is a collection of
   biographical essays on the lives of the most important people in legal
   scholarship from the 12^th to the 18^th Century.

   Throughout the work, Hommel conscientiously relates to the problems of
   reducing a guidebook for the literature of the law to the size of a
   single volume, explaining his method and his outlook at each turn.Â  In
   the preface to the [22]first edition of the work (1761), he suggests
   that a handful of the essays from the first half of the work will give
   you the keys to developing a highly scaled down, but excellent
   collection of law books: "notitia librorum exhibetur, neque tamen
   omnium, sed classicorum tantum, quos si quis possideat, de parva
   quidem, sed splendida et selectissima iuris bibliotheca sibi gratulari
   possit."Â  But what's the price of scaling down a collection?Â  Sifting
   out the lesser creatures...


